# Status Update terminal rule (P26 §3b)

When you emit a **Status Update**, it is the **end of your message**. Stop typing after `### Approval needed` (or after `### Next priority` if approval is none).

## Next priority = exactly one executable story

- Run `pnpm agent:next-work` in the **owner repo** for that story.
- **One** bullet under **Next priority** — the story you will execute next.
- **Never** list two stories (e.g. W2-OPS-001 and IR-3.5) then ask which to do.

| Wrong | Right |
| ----- | ----- |
| Next priority lists W2-OPS-001 **and** IR-3.5, then "Want me to proceed with IR-3.5 or stay on W2?" | **Next priority** = W2-OPS-001 only (in_progress wins over pending backlog) |
| Paragraph after Approval needed | **Stop.** Class R: start W2-OPS-001 in the same or next turn without asking |

## Backlog / pending items

Put **pending** work (IR-3.5, etc.) in **Done** as context or a single line "Deferred: IR-3.5" — **not** as a second Next priority and **never** as a question.

## Hard-forbidden (after Status Update)

- `Want me to proceed with … or …?`
- `Should I switch to … or stay on …?`
- `Which would you like?`
- Any `?` that asks the operator to pick between two stories

## Class R

If **Next priority** is Class R and you have shell access: **begin that work** — do not ask permission to start the item you already named.
